### 4.1.4 Feature Distribution Analysis

> **[Insert: Figure 4.1 — Baseline Feature Distribution Histograms]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.1: Baseline Feature Distribution Histograms*

**Interpretation:** The baseline feature distribution histograms reveal the statistical properties of each feature in the training dataset. Features exhibiting approximately normal distributions have predictable drift ranges, while skewed features require careful threshold calibration. These distributions serve as the reference point for drift detection — any significant deviation from these patterns in incoming inference data triggers the monitoring engine's alert system.

### 4.1.5 Correlation Analysis

> **[Insert: Figure 4.2 — Correlation Heatmap of Features]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.2: Correlation Heatmap of Features*

**Interpretation:** The correlation heatmap displays pairwise Pearson correlation coefficients between all numeric features. Strong positive correlations (r > 0.7) between feature pairs indicate potential multicollinearity, which the feature selection module addresses during training. Weakly correlated features contribute independent information to the model. This analysis informs the feature selection phase of the training pipeline.

### 4.1.6 Target Class Distribution

> **[Insert: Figure 4.3 — Target Variable Class Distribution (Bar Chart)]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.3: Target Variable Class Distribution*

**Interpretation:** The bar chart shows the distribution of target classes. Class imbalance, where one class significantly outnumbers others, can bias model predictions. The platform's training pipeline includes a SMOTE-based data rebalancing phase activated when the imbalance ratio exceeds a configurable threshold, ensuring equitable performance across all classes.

