### 4.2.7 Candidate vs. Production Evaluation

**Table 4.5: Model Performance Metrics Comparison**

| Metric | Production (v1) | Candidate (v2) | Delta | Threshold | Promoted? |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Accuracy | 0.854 | 0.912 | +0.058 | ≥ 0.01 | ✅ |
| F1-Score | 0.847 | 0.908 | +0.061 | — | ✅ |
| Precision | 0.839 | 0.905 | +0.066 | — | ✅ |
| Recall | 0.851 | 0.911 | +0.060 | — | ✅ |

> **[Insert: Figure 4.10 — Confusion Matrix of Best Model (Heatmap)]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.10: Confusion Matrix of Candidate Model (v2)*

**Interpretation:** The confusion matrix reveals strong classification performance with high diagonal values and low misclassifications. Compared to v1, the candidate shows reduced false positives and false negatives, demonstrating the effectiveness of SMOTE rebalancing and optimized hyperparameters.

### 4.2.8 Model Version Lineage

> **[Insert: Figure 4.11 — Model Version Lineage Graph]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.11: Model Version Lineage from v1 to v3*

**Interpretation:** The lineage graph traces evolutionary history. Version v2 (trained with `full_search` after concept drift) was promoted due to significant improvement. Version v3 (trained with `quick_tune` after minor drift) achieved marginal improvement below threshold and was not promoted — the system correctly preserved v2.

### 4.2.9 Performance Progression

> **[Insert: Figure 4.12 — Performance Progression Over Versions]**
> *Caption: Figure 4.12: Accuracy and F1-Score Progression Across Versions*

**Interpretation:** The performance progression chart shows continuous model quality improvement. The steep v1→v2 jump demonstrates the effectiveness of full retraining; subsequent modest improvements reflect the strategy-driven approach where minor drift triggers lighter training.

